OWASP Top 10 (2025) Room

📌 Overview

This repository documents my learning progress through a cybersecurity training room focused on the OWASP Top 10 (2025) vulnerabilities.
The goal of this log is to track key concepts, understand real-world risks, and reinforce secure coding practices through hands-on learning.

🎯 Objectives
Understand common web application vulnerabilities
Learn how attackers exploit insecure systems
Explore mitigation and secure design strategies
Build a strong foundation in application security
🔍 Topics Covered
🛑 A01: Broken Access Control

Broken Access Control occurs when users can act outside their intended permissions.

Key Learnings:

Horizontal privilege escalation (accessing other users’ data)
Vertical privilege escalation (gaining admin access)
Insecure direct object references (IDOR)
Missing or improperly enforced authorization checks

Impact:

Unauthorized data access
Account takeover
Exposure of sensitive information

Prevention:

Enforce server-side access control checks
Use role-based access control (RBAC)
Avoid trusting client-side input for authorization
⚙️ A07: Identification and Authentication Failures

This category focuses on weaknesses in authentication mechanisms.

Key Learnings:

Weak password policies
Lack of multi-factor authentication (MFA)
Session mismanagement (predictable or reused session IDs)
Credential stuffing and brute-force attacks

Impact:

Account compromise
Unauthorized system access

Prevention:

Implement strong password policies
Use MFA
Secure session handling (timeouts, regeneration)
Rate limiting and login protections
📦 A09: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures

Failures in logging and monitoring reduce visibility into attacks.

Key Learnings:

Missing or insufficient logging
Lack of real-time monitoring
Poor incident detection capabilities

Impact:

Delayed detection of breaches
Inability to investigate attacks
Increased damage due to unnoticed intrusions

Prevention:

Implement centralized logging
Monitor authentication and access events
Use alerting systems for suspicious activities
Regularly review logs
🧠 Key Takeaways
Security must be enforced server-side, not trusted to users
Authentication and authorization are separate but equally critical
Logging is essential for detection and response, not just debugging
Real-world vulnerabilities often result from simple misconfigurations
